01:09:20,346 --> 01:09:20,626
[SPEAKER_03]: Jenny?

771
01:09:20,646 --> 01:09:21,347
[SPEAKER_03]: Maria?

772
01:09:23,148 --> 01:09:26,251
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes, it's just a word change, I guess.

773
01:09:28,593 --> 01:09:31,555
[SPEAKER_03]: At 2.2 where it says adequately sized spaces,

774
01:09:33,078 --> 01:09:41,182
[SPEAKER_03]: The other categories say that it meets, it optimizes, it provides, but for the size, it's just saying adequately sized.

775
01:09:42,023 --> 01:09:49,887
[SPEAKER_03]: Wouldn't it be better to say optimally sized or maximize spaces as opposed to just adequate?

776
01:09:52,508 --> 01:09:53,328
[SPEAKER_13]: That's a great question.

777
01:09:53,408 --> 01:09:59,672
[SPEAKER_13]: Matt, do you have any thoughts about that topic and how you would rate or evaluate that?

778
01:10:04,808 --> 01:10:11,073
[SPEAKER_01]: I think optimally might be a good replacement word in terms of adequately that's listed in there.

779
01:10:13,055 --> 01:10:23,143
[SPEAKER_01]: It does have a more positive connotation to it and I think it's sort of aspiring to something as opposed to just sort of saying it's at a baseline.

780
01:10:24,751 --> 01:10:30,953
[SPEAKER_01]: potentially we get into discussion of sort of what adequate versus optimal means.

781
01:10:31,193 --> 01:10:38,335
[SPEAKER_01]: But I think in this case, optimal does sound like a better and maybe more consistent word usage here.

782
01:10:42,857 --> 01:10:48,639
[SPEAKER_13]: Paul Malone, did you have a related question or should I wrap this one up before we move to you?

783
01:10:50,159 --> 01:10:51,780
[SPEAKER_16]: It's a comment about the current question.

784
01:10:51,800 --> 01:10:53,000
[SPEAKER_13]: Okay, go ahead.

785
01:10:54,320 --> 01:11:00,345
[SPEAKER_16]: Um, I, I think adequately does seem a little bit out of place because the words are so dynamic for the rest of these.

786
01:11:00,365 --> 01:11:08,051
[SPEAKER_16]: I would just caution against using maximize because I think an appropriate space size for some of these uses would be actually smaller rather than larger.

787
01:11:08,071 --> 01:11:08,912
[SPEAKER_16]: It could be too big.

788
01:11:09,552 --> 01:11:15,537
[SPEAKER_16]: Um, I would support optimize, um, as an alternative and more powerful piece of language.

789
01:11:18,319 --> 01:11:21,982
[SPEAKER_13]: And Paul Rousseau, are you, do you have a comment related to this question?

790
01:11:22,621 --> 01:11:29,448
[SPEAKER_00]: I do, and I think I'm a little bit of an outlier here on the opinions on this, but adequately to me is another word for minimal.

791
01:11:31,870 --> 01:11:39,257
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, a bathroom could be adequately sized to meet ADA standards, which to me means minimal.

792
01:11:41,018 --> 01:11:42,079
[SPEAKER_00]: We can't go smaller.

793
01:11:42,680 --> 01:11:44,482
[SPEAKER_00]: And when I see the word adequately, I think

794
01:11:45,673 --> 01:11:47,233
[SPEAKER_00]: That's what is meant by that.

795
01:11:48,013 --> 01:11:49,414
[SPEAKER_00]: Is it the best option?

796
01:11:49,454 --> 01:11:55,195
[SPEAKER_00]: Does it give us the most options for how we might want to change education in the future or flexibility?

797
01:11:55,695 --> 01:12:05,876
[SPEAKER_00]: No, adequate to me means, will people be able to be in the place and get an education?

798
01:12:06,937 --> 01:12:14,578
[SPEAKER_00]: So optimized to me doesn't, I certainly understand, I like the word optimized in other places here, but optimized implies,

799
01:12:15,470 --> 01:12:22,576
[SPEAKER_00]: an enormous amount of knowledge to know whether something's optimized and the many different uses.

800
01:12:24,117 --> 01:12:44,574
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, I mean, I'm not a teacher, but if an English class is, you know, everybody's sitting in rows staring at the whiteboard or in a math class or something, that might be optimal, but then a different kind of class in that same space might not be optimal or not even be adequate.

801
01:12:45,673 --> 01:12:52,297
[SPEAKER_00]: So I, I don't know that there's the conversation point, I think, but adequately to me always has meant minimum.

802
01:12:57,299 --> 01:12:57,780
[SPEAKER_08]: May I just say.

803
01:12:59,947 --> 01:13:12,495
[SPEAKER_08]: I think what's important that Paul just brought up, though, based on one of his examples is, does this say, Matt, parentheses, educational, because these are all classroom spaces we're talking about.

804
01:13:12,515 --> 01:13:16,918
[SPEAKER_08]: They're not office spaces, toilet spaces.

805
01:13:17,319 --> 01:13:23,463
